WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:04.864
Lung cancer is one of the most critical
respiratory conditions you'll encounter as a

2
00:00:04.864 --> 00:00:07.764
respiratory therapist, not just because of
its severity,

3
00:00:08.204 --> 00:00:13.585
but because of how often it presents late
and affects both ventilation and oxygenation.

4
00:00:13.645 --> 00:00:17.584
At its core, lung cancer is uncontrolled
cell growth in

5
00:00:17.584 --> 00:00:20.245
lung tissue that disrupts normal gas
exchange.

6
00:00:20.864 --> 00:00:23.264
As tumors grow, they can obstruct airways,

7
00:00:23.864 --> 00:00:27.485
compress surrounding structures, and
create ventilation-perfusion mismatch.

8
00:00:28.125 --> 00:00:31.165
This leads to hypoxemia, increased work of
breathing,

9
00:00:31.704 --> 00:00:34.224
and, in advanced cases, respiratory
failure.

10
00:00:34.525 --> 00:00:37.825
There are two main categories to know,
non-small cell

11
00:00:37.825 --> 00:00:40.805
lung cancer, which is more common and
typically slower growing,

12
00:00:41.284 --> 00:00:44.384
and small cell lung cancer, which is more
aggressive and

13
00:00:44.384 --> 00:00:44.845
spreads rapidly.

14
00:00:45.264 --> 00:00:49.064
For board exams and clinical practice,
always connect the type

15
00:00:49.064 --> 00:00:53.904
of cancer to how quickly symptoms progress
and how urgently intervention is needed.

16
00:00:54.224 --> 00:00:57.424
From an RT perspective, think in terms of
cause,

17
00:00:58.185 --> 00:00:59.125
effect, and intervention.

18
00:01:00.084 --> 00:01:02.865
Tumor growth causes airway obstruction or
alveolar damage.

19
00:01:03.444 --> 00:01:06.025
That leads to symptoms like dyspnea,
cough,

20
00:01:06.584 --> 00:01:08.644
hemoptysis, and decreased breath sounds.

21
00:01:09.184 --> 00:01:14.245
Your role is to assess how much this is
affecting ventilation and oxygenation and

22
00:01:14.245 --> 00:01:15.264
respond appropriately.

23
00:01:16.385 --> 00:01:17.485
Diagnostics are key.

24
00:01:18.364 --> 00:01:30.144
Imaging like chest ABGs and oxygen
saturation tell you how well the patient is

25
00:01:30.144 --> 00:01:31.605
oxygenating and ventilating.

26
00:01:32.444 --> 00:01:35.565
Always interpret these together, not in
isolation.

27
00:01:36.264 --> 00:01:38.705
Management depends on stage and severity.

28
00:01:39.385 --> 00:01:41.964
Early stage disease may be treated with
surgery.

29
00:01:42.665 --> 00:01:46.065
More advanced disease often requires
chemotherapy, radiation,

30
00:01:46.285 --> 00:01:47.444
or targeted therapy.

31
00:01:47.584 --> 00:01:51.805
But regardless of treatment, RTs play a
major role in

32
00:01:51.805 --> 00:01:55.165
supportive care, oxygen therapy, airway
clearance,

33
00:01:55.544 --> 00:01:58.944
bronchodilators when indicated, and
monitoring for complications.

34
00:01:59.824 --> 00:02:04.845
Red flags you must recognize include
hemoptysis, rapid worsening dyspnea,

35
00:02:05.544 --> 00:02:09.404
hypoxemia that doesn't respond to oxygen,
and signs of airway

36
00:02:09.404 --> 00:02:10.664
obstruction or collapse.

37
00:02:11.205 --> 00:02:13.264
These require immediate escalation.

38
00:02:13.565 --> 00:02:16.985
In real clinical scenarios, your decisions
matter.

39
00:02:16.985 --> 00:02:19.065
You're not just treating symptoms.

40
00:02:19.625 --> 00:02:23.264
You're identifying deterioration early,
supporting gas exchange,

41
00:02:23.464 --> 00:02:25.604
and helping guide the next step in care.

42
00:02:25.705 --> 00:02:29.464
If you remember one thing, lung cancer is
not just

43
00:02:29.464 --> 00:02:29.904
a tumor.

44
00:02:30.244 --> 00:02:33.884
It's a progressive disruption of
ventilation and oxygenation.

45
00:02:34.404 --> 00:02:38.205
Your job is to recognize that disruption,
quantify it,

46
00:02:38.205 --> 00:02:40.324
and act quickly to support the patient.

